    "title": "IU football coach Curt Cignetti still thinks Hoosiers are CFP worthy",
    "text": "Is IU football a CFP team? 'Is that a serious question? ... The answer is so obvious.' Michael Niziolek The Herald-Times COLUMBUS, Ohio — IU football coach Curt Cignetti had a straight-to-the-point response when asked if his team was deserving of a spot in the College Football Playoff after a 38-15 loss to Ohio State on Saturday.\n\"Is that a serious question?\" Cignetti said.\nThe No. 5 Hoosiers (10-1, 7-1 Big Ten ) came into the game with the weakest strength of schedule among the country's top 12 teams. The CFP committee said publicly they were paying close attention to IU's performance down the stretch that included games against Michigan and the Buckeyes.\nDoyel: Ohio State 'sucks'? OSU's Ryan Day sends Curt Cignetti a message. Now IU awaits CFP.\nHayes: Even a loss to Ohio State can't stop IU from Playoff\nWhen pressed for a response, Cignetti didn't need to say much to get his point across.\n\"I'm not even going to answer that because the answer is so obvious,\" Cignetti said.\nIndiana has won double-digit games for the first time in program history and the team's 10-0 start was also a new best. The Hoosiers were one of just three remaining unbeaten teams in the country before losing to the Buckeyes and had won all but one of their games by 14 or more points.\nCignetti talked about the \"narrative\" surrounding IU's schedule in a pre-game interview with ESPN but wasn't interested in rehashing the conversation.\n\"I don't make those decisions,\" Cignetti said after the game \"I think the probably more important right now, we have to focus on our next game, big in-state rival in Purdue, which Indiana hasn't beaten in how long? Since '19. That needs to be the focus.\"\nMichael Niziolek is the Indiana beat reporter for The Bloomington Herald-Times. You can follow him on X @michaelniziolek and read all his coverage by clicking here .\nFacebook\nTwitter\nEmail",
